04731nam a22007455i 9780231541480DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015029465  a(OCoLC)979575565  a97802315414807 a10.7312/dale176082doi  a(DE-B1597)473331  a(OCoLC)948826672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHB102.P64bD348 2016 4aHB102.P64bD348 2017 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a330.15420922231 aDale, Gareth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKarl Polanyi :bA Life on the Left /cGareth Dale. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. In the East- West Salon -- tTwo. Bearing the Cross of War -- tThree. Triumph and Tragedy of Red Vienna -- tFour. Challenges and Responses -- tFive. The Cataclysm and Its Origins -- tSix “Injustices and Inhumanities” -- tSeven. The Precariousness of Existence -- tEpilogue. A Lost World of Socialism -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKarl Polanyi (1886–1964) was one of the twentieth century's most original interpreters of the market economy. His penetrating analysis of globalization's disruptions and the Great Depression's underlying causes still serves as an effective counterargument to free market fundamentalism. This biography shows how the major personal and historical events of his life transformed him from a bourgeois radical into a Christian socialist but also informed his ambivalent stance on social democracy, communism, the New Deal, and the shifting intellectual scene of postwar America.The book begins with Polanyi's childhood in the Habsburg Empire and his involvement with the Great War and Hungary's postwar revolution. It connects Polanyi's idealistic radicalism to the political promise and intellectual ferment of Red Vienna and the horror of fascism. The narrative revisits Polanyi's oeuvre in English, German, and Hungarian, includes exhaustive research in five archives, and features interviews with Polanyi's daughter, students, and colleagues, clarifying the contradictory aspects of the thinker's work. These personal accounts also shed light on Polanyi's connections to scholars, Christians, atheists, journalists, hot and cold warriors, and socialists of all stripes. Karl Polanyi: A Life on the Left engages with Polanyi's biography as a reflection and condensation of extraordinary times. It highlights the historical ruptures, tensions, and upheavals that the thinker sought to capture and comprehend and, in telling his story, engages with the intellectual and political history of a turbulent epoch.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomicsxHistory. 0aEconomistszHungaryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/dale1760840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231541480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231541480/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DEGb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016